# personal-id-forbidden.regex
#
# Patterns that MUST NOT appear in any shipped framework artefact
# (cli/, skills/, agents/, commands/, templates/, scripts/, dev-tools/,
# CLAUDE.md, README.md, docs/).
#
# Format: one extended-regex pattern per non-empty, non-comment line.
# Lines starting with `#` are comments. Each pattern is matched
# case-insensitively via perl -CSD (UTF-8-safe; BSD-compatible).
#
# Inline exclusion fence: lines between
#   <!-- gate:example-only -->
# and
#   <!-- /gate:example-only -->
# are exempt (counter-examples and teaching content).
#
# Consumers may extend this by pointing --regex at their own merged file.
# Do NOT add ecosystem-specific entries here — keep the framework contract
# neutral. Consumer extensions belong in the consumer's local copy.

# Operator personal handles / names (word-boundary, case-insensitive)
\bpavel\b
\bvalentov\b
\bpaxbeach\b
\byuval\b

# Ecosystem-specific hostnames / project names
\barcana-dev\b

# Ecosystem-specific Vault/credential paths
arcanada/aether

# Personal Asana PAT variable names (any ASANA_*_PAT pattern)
ASANA_[A-Z_]*PAT

# 16-digit numeric IDs (Asana workspace/user GIDs)
\b[0-9]{16}\b

# Real public IPv4 heuristic — forward leak prevention.
# The specific IPs below stay as a defense-in-depth denylist, but the FLOOR is
# now a heuristic in scripts/personal-id-gate.sh (sub is_real_public_ipv4): it
# flags ANY routable public IPv4 in the shipped surface, so a NEW unlisted
# ecosystem IP is caught without touching this file. Reserved/documentation
# ranges (RFC 1918, RFC 5737 TEST-NET, loopback, link-local, 100.64/10 CGNAT,
# 4th-octet-0 network/version strings) are excluded there. Keep this denylist
# in sync when hosts change, but the heuristic no longer depends on it.

# Arcana production infrastructure — real public IPs (never in shipped surface)
\b49\.13\.52\.208\b
\b65\.108\.236\.39\b
\b135\.181\.222\.38\b
\b37\.27\.107\.227\b

# Arcana production infrastructure — Tailscale mesh IPs
\b100\.78\.174\.28\b
\b100\.121\.155\.54\b
\b100\.70\.137\.104\b
\b100\.90\.7\.20\b

# ssh root@ to a literal IPv4 (entry-point leak — use ssh root@<host> placeholder instead)
ssh root@[0-9]{1,3}\.[0-9]{1,3}\.[0-9]{1,3}\.[0-9]{1,3}
